article.headline: Allen sub Murray Sonics' high scorer
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Some folks around the NBA might be surprised to see Ronald "Flip" Murray leading the Seattle SuperSonics in Ray Allen's absence. Murray isn't one of them. Filling in while Allen recovers from ankle surgery, Murray scored 24 points to lead Seattle to a 100-82 victory over the Portland Trail Blazers on Friday night. "It's me," Murray said. "I know what I'm capable of. I'm just finally getting a chance to show it." Rashard Lewis added 21 points in Seattle's home opener, Brent Barry 20 and Vladimir Radmanovic 19 for the Sonics, who played for the first time in the week since a season-opening two-game series in Japan. At 3-0, they're the only unbeaten team left in the league. Rasheed Wallace scored 25 for Portland and Zach Randolph had 19 as the Blazers took advantage of their size advantage in the first half. The Sonics, though, eventually offset that with defense and outside shooting, outscoring the Blazers 32-18 in the third period. "They had more energy, for whatever reason," Portland coach Maurice Cheeks said. "Their matchup zone bothered us." Bonzi Wells scored 13. He continued to play after hurting his knee in a collision with Seattle's Reggie Evans in the first quarter. The game was delayed late in the third when the horn malfunctioned and wouldn't stop for five minutes. The noisy problem, linked to a power failure, was solved by turning off the scoreboard above center court the rest of the night. Murray, who shot 9-of-14 from the floor, was one of the little-known names in the blockbuster trade that sent Gary Payton from Seattle to Milwaukee last season for Allen. With Allen on the injured list and expected to miss at least six weeks, Murray has shined in Seattle's three games. "We all know this is Ray Allen's team," said Murray, who grew up in Philadelphia and played at Shaw College in North Carolina. "We're all just waiting for him to come back. We want him back on the floor." Murray scored 24 and 22 points as the Sonics swept a two-game series against the Los Angeles Clippers last week in Japan, and showed no signs of slowing despite the one-week break that followed. "Flip has been solid," coach Nate McMillan said. "This is his third 20-point game and I think defensively he's playing a good game for us. He has stepped in and given us something we needed." The Sonics led 64-60 in the third when Murray scored seven straight points. He drove for a basket, then beat the 24-second clock with a 3-pointer on a feed from Barry and added two free throws as Seattle pulled away. "That (No.) 22 kid, I should know who he is. He's from Philly," said Cheeks, a standout point guard for the 76ers during his playing days. "I should know his name." Allen was expected to attend the home opener, but he stayed in Los Angeles, where he is recovering from surgery to repair his right ankle. Wallace, meanwhile, was up to his old tricks for the Blazers. Known for his combustible personality and NBA single-season record of 41 technical fouls in 2000-01, Wallace got his first technical of the season with 9:09 to play in the third after protesting what he felt was a push in the back by Lewis.

Game notes
George Karl, who coached Seattle from 1991-98, returned as a television analyst. ... The Blazers placed G Derek Anderson on the injured list before tipoff because of back spasms and signed Matt Carroll, a free agent rookie who suited up but didn't play until garbage time. ... The Northwest rivals have played 173 games in 34 seasons, with the Sonics narrowly leading the series 87-86.
